Add one more vote highly opposed to this idea.  Craig hit some of the key
arguments.  When the domain system was younger, I saw an awful lot of mail
getting out with hostnames that could not be found in either the host table
or domain system.

Let just say that anyone with a bit of knowledge could find out a fair
amount about what types of host exists, their address, their hostnames
(login prompts, mailers, ftp), etc.  You don't end up hiding much.  If
you want to hide host names, use nondescriptive domain names such as
host1.domain5.msc.umn.edu.  I can't tell much from this and I don't think
anyone else can either.  This solves your problem with companies at least.

As for gateways and terminal servers, I don't think there is any reason to
keep them hidden.  Some of the terminal servers now available use the name
server fopr host lookups and can connect to anyplace.  I would like to be
able to track down where connections are coming from.

					Jim

